    {
      "title": "E. theSUM ‚Äî the sum analysis of plural the (Exercise 10)",
      "instructions": "Before the supremum analysis, the book first tries treating plural the as the generalized sum: theSUM ‚áù ŒªP.‚äïP (entry 33), where ‚äïP is the sum of all the P's (type e). For \"the singers\" this gives the right answer ‚Äî the maximal singer-sum. But notice the second item: with \"two singers\", theSUM sums up ALL the two-singer pluralities, collapsing them back to the total sum ‚Äî so \"theSUM two singers\" wrongly denotes the sum of all singers, not a pair. This is exactly why the book replaces theSUM with theSUPR. (Here two ‚áù Œªx.card(x)=2 combines with singers by Predicate Modification.)",
      "items": [
